Dear Mennix,<br><br>I have been in the habit of perusing your letters for a bit of advice and the occasional smile. Is there a way of reading your older letters?<br><br>I must confess that I would like to read some of your earlier works.<br><br>-Tirra Jorg<br>Barbarian shaman<br><br>Dear Mennix,<br><br>Being a halfling with copious advice and wisdom to share with your fellow travelers, how is it that you are content to simply let the passage of time erase your teachings?  I would expect someone who is obviously a great scholar such as yourself to have amassed a large collection of helpful advice which would surely benefit the masses greatly by being available for perusal?<br><br>How is it that such an oversight could occur?  I feel saddened every time events conspire that I miss your words.<br><br>-Krelnor of the wooded elves<br><br><b>Dear Tirra and Krelnor,<br><br>I will be opening an archive soon. This archive will include all my past letters. Long ago, back when the tavern first opened, there was an archive where I used to deposit old letters, and then I made the foolish mistake of hiring an ogre to do some cleaning around here. <br><br>You would not believe this, but I was sitting at my desk one day when I saw Goop, the ogre in question, walking out to the outhouse with a bundle of papers in his hand. At first, I thought nothing of it. Then I remembered what task I had set him on just that morning. He was to enter the archive and do a bit of dusting. Needless to say, once this memory hit my brain, my feet hit the floor, and I was out running towards Goop, who was now in the outhouse whistling. I threw open the door with the mind to save my works, and Goop stopped whistling.<br><br>No matter what you think of me or the advice I give, I plead with you all to heed the advice I am about to give.<br><br>NEVER enter an outhouse after an ogre has been in it.<br><br>I threw open that door and before I could utter one accusatory word, my eyes began to burn, my skin itched, and the most rancid green cloud wafted out from the outhouse surrounding my body in a most putrid stench. I stumbled backward, and before passing out, saw Goop shrug, close the door, and continue to whistle his little tune.<br><br>I am sure no one will blame me for not recovering those original letters.</b><br><br><br>
